{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/d-d-when-to-choose-a-worse-roll-type-for-a-larger-modifier-b5a4eb37409d", "time": 1683003114.062407, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/d-d-when-to-choose-a-worse-roll-type-for-a-larger-modifier-b5a4eb37409d/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "D&D: When to Choose a Worse Roll Type for a Larger Modifier | by Dan VanLunen (DVL) | Towards Data Science", "h1": "D&D: When to Choose a Worse Roll Type for a Larger Modifier", "description": "While listening to Matt Mercer DM Dungeons and Dragons on Critical Role, I sometimes hear him offer a choice to the players: For example, if you are a monk trying to scale large pile of rocks, you\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://critrole.com/", "anchor_text": "Critical Role", "paragraph_index": 0}], "all_paragraphs": ["While listening to Matt Mercer DM Dungeons and Dragons on Critical Role, I sometimes hear him offer a choice to the players:", "For example, if you are a monk trying to scale large pile of rocks, you may roll a straight athletics check (choice 1.) to pull yourself up. The DM may also offer that you could roll an acrobatics check (and you have a higher acrobatics modifier because you have a high Dex) with disadvantage hopping along the rocks (choice 2.). The value you need total to succeed on the check is the same for either roll: e.g., 15 (this value is called the DC).", "How should you choose? Well, the choice should reflect your character and what they would do.", "However, if you want to maximize the chance that you will succeed on the check, then use the following algorithm. Note you could also imagine that you could get the choice between i) advantage (two d20 and take the higher value) and a natural roll or ii) advantage and a disadvantage roll, so the algorithm takes that into account as well.", "A good rule of thumb is that you should be willing to step down one (advantage to natural or natural to disadvantage) or two (advantage to disadvantage) levels if the task is very hard because there is no chance you\u2019ll succeed without that additional modifier bonus. You should also be willing to step down one level if the difference in modifiers is 5 or greater.", "If you are wondering: \u201cWhat is this foul magic: how was this chart created?\u201d, read on.", "Let\u2019s start with the basics. When you roll a d20, there is an equal 5% chance of any number 1 to 20 being rolled: rolling a d20 is drawing from the discrete uniform distribution between 1 and 20. This distribution is shown in the plot below.", "However, what we really care about is the chance we will succeed: the total chance greater than or equal to the DC (e.g. the total area of the bars to the right of the vertical red line representing a DC of 15). Mathematically, what we really care about is:", "This is a simple formula for one roll. For two rolls, we can take advantage of the fact that the rolls are independent (so the probability of something happening on both rolls is the square of it happening on one roll) and plug in the simple formula.", "Now, we can use these formulas in code to determine which type of roll should be chosen for each modifier difference and adjusted DC.", "The dataset created by the above looks like the below. The first two columns show the x and y axis for the magical chart (adjusted DC and modifier difference). The next 4 columns shown below are the probability of passing the check with a certain type of roll. The last 3 columns shown below tell you which type of roll to choose to maximize the probability of success.", "We can then pivot this data to make it easier to plot.", "Finally, we can send the data into the chart.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Data Science Manager \u2014 Causal Inference, Prediction, Data Engineering"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fb5a4eb37409d&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButt